[src:mobx/observable-state] Properties, entire objects, arrays, Maps and Sets can all be made observable.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The basics of making objects observable is specifying an annotation per property using `makeObservable`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] This function can be used to make *existing* object properties observable.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Any JavaScript object (including class instances) can be passed into `target`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Typically `makeObservable` is used in the constructor of a class, and its first argument is `this`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The `annotations` argument maps annotations to each member.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Alternatively, decorators like `@observable` can be used on class members instead of calling `makeObservable` in the constructor.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Methods that derive information and take arguments (for example `findUsersOlderThan(age: number): User[]`) can not be annotated as `computed` – their read operations will still be tracked when they are called from a reaction, but their output won't be memoized to avoid memory leaks.
[src:mobx/observable-state] To memoize such methods you can use MobX-utils computedFn {🚀} instead.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Subclassing is supported with some limitations by using the `override` annotation (see the example here).
[src:mobx/observable-state] When using modern decorators, there is no need to call `makeObservable`, below is what a decorator based class looks like.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Note that the `@observable` annotation should always be used in combination with the `accessor` keyword.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Note that classes can leverage `makeAutoObservable` as well.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The difference in the examples just demonstrates how MobX can be applied to different programming styles.
[src:mobx/observable-state] In contrast to the first example with `makeObservable`, `observable` supports adding (and removing) *fields* to an object.
[src:mobx/observable-state] This makes `observable` great for collections like dynamically keyed objects, arrays, Maps and Sets.
[src:mobx/observable-state] To use legacy decorators, `makeObservable(this)` should be called in the constructor to make sure decorators work.
[src:mobx/observable-state] `makeAutoObservable` is like `makeObservable` on steroids, as it infers all the properties by default.
[src:mobx/observable-state] You can however use the `overrides` parameter to override the default behavior with specific annotations — in particular `false` can be used to exclude a property or method from being processed entirely.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Check out the code above for an example.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The `makeAutoObservable` function can be more compact and easier to maintain than using `makeObservable`, since new members don't have to be mentioned explicitly.
[src:mobx/observable-state] However, `makeAutoObservable` cannot be used on classes that have super or are subclassed.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The `observable` annotation can also be called as a function to make an entire object observable at once.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The `source` object will be cloned and all members will be made observable, similar to how it would be done by `makeAutoObservable`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Likewise, an `overrides` map can be provided to specify the annotations of specific members.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Check out the above code block for an example.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The object returned by `observable` will be a Proxy, which means that properties that are added later to the object will be picked up and made observable as well (except when proxy usage is disabled).
[src:mobx/observable-state] The `observable` method can also be called with collections types like arrays, Maps and Sets.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Those will be cloned as well and converted into their observable counterparts.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The following example creates an observable and observes it using `autorun`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Working with Map and Set collections works similarly.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Primitive values cannot be made observable by MobX since they are immutable in JavaScript (but they can be boxed).
[src:mobx/observable-state] Although there is typically no use for this mechanism outside libraries.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Class instances will never be made observable automatically by passing them to `observable` or assigning them to an `observable` property.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Making class members observable is considered the responsibility of the class constructor.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The primary difference between `make(Auto)Observable` and `observable` is that the first one modifies the object you are passing in as first argument, while `observable` creates a *clone* that is made observable.
[src:mobx/observable-state] The second difference is that `observable` creates a `Proxy` object, to be able to trap future property additions in case you use the object as a dynamic lookup map.
[src:mobx/observable-state] If the object you want to make observable has a regular structure where all members are known up-front, we recommend to use `makeObservable` as non proxied objects are a little faster, and they are easier to inspect in the debugger and `console.log`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Because of that, `make(Auto)Observable` is the recommended API to use in factory functions.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Note that it is possible to pass `{ proxy: false }` as an option to `observable` to get a non proxied clone.
[src:mobx/observable-state] `makeObservable` can only annotate properties declared by its own class definition.
[src:mobx/observable-state] If a sub- or superclass introduces observable fields, it will have to call `makeObservable` for those properties itself.
[src:mobx/observable-state] `options` argument can be provided only once.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Passed `options` are *"sticky"* and can NOT be changed later (eg. in subclass).
[src:mobx/observable-state] **Every field can be annotated only once** (except for `override`).
[src:mobx/observable-state] The field annotation or configuration can't change in subclass.
[src:mobx/observable-state] **All annotated** fields of non-plain objects (**classes**) are **non-configurable**.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Can be disabled with `configure({ safeDescriptors: false })` {🚀☣️} .
[src:mobx/observable-state] **All non-observable** (stateless) fields (`action`, `flow`) are **non-writable**.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Only **`action`, `computed`, `flow`, `action.bound`** defined **on prototype** can be **overridden** by subclass.
[src:mobx/observable-state] By default *TypeScript* will not allow you to annotate **private** fields.
[src:mobx/observable-state] **Calling `make(Auto)Observable`** and providing annotations must be done **unconditionally**, as this makes it possible to cache the inference results.
[src:mobx/observable-state] **Modifying prototypes** after **`make(Auto)Observable`** has been called is **not supported**.
[src:mobx/observable-state] *EcmaScript* **private** fields (**`#field`**) are **not supported** by `make(Auto)Observable`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Use auto-accessor + Stage-3 decorators (`@observable accessor #field`) syntax instead.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Otherwise, when using *TypeScript*, it is recommended to use the `private` modifier.
[src:mobx/observable-state] **Mixing annotations and decorators** within single inheritance chain is **not supported** - eg. you can't use decorators for superclass and annotations for subclass.
[src:mobx/observable-state] `makeObservable(Object.create(prototype))` copies properties from `prototype` to created object and makes them `observable`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] This behavior is wrong, unexpected and therefore **deprecated** and will likely change in future versions.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Sometimes it is necessary to convert observable data structures back to their vanilla counterparts.
[src:mobx/observable-state] For example when passing observable objects to a React component that can't track observables, or to obtain a clone that should not be further mutated.
[src:mobx/observable-state] To convert a data tree recursively to plain objects, the `toJS` utility can be used.
[src:mobx/observable-state] For classes, it is recommended to implement a `toJSON()` method, as it will be picked up by `JSON.stringify`.
[src:mobx/observable-state] So far most examples above have been leaning towards the class syntax.
[src:mobx/observable-state] MobX is in principle unopinionated about this, and there are probably just as many MobX users that use plain objects.
[src:mobx/observable-state] However, a slight benefit of classes is that they have more easily discoverable APIs, e.g.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Also, `instanceof` checks are really powerful for type inference, and class instances aren't wrapped in `Proxy` objects, giving them a better experience in debuggers.
[src:mobx/observable-state] Finally, classes benefit from a lot of engine optimizations, since their shape is predictable, and methods are shared on the prototype.
[src:mobx/observable-state] But heavy inheritance patterns can easily become foot-guns, so if you use classes, keep them simple.
[src:mobx/observable-state] So, even though there is a slight preference to use classes, we definitely want to encourage you to deviate from this style if that suits you better.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The subject knows its observers through a standardized interface and manages the subscription list directly.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This pattern creates a one-to-many dependency where multiple observers can listen to a single subject, but the coupling is typically synchronous and direct—the subject calls observer methods when changes occur, though asynchronous implementations using event queues are possible.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Unlike the publish-subscribe pattern, there is no intermediary broker; the subject and observers have direct references to each other.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] It is commonly used to implement event handling systems in event-driven programming, particularly in-process systems like GUI toolkits or MVC frameworks.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This makes the pattern well-suited to processing data that arrives unpredictably—such as user input, HTTP requests, GPIO signals, updates from distributed databases, or changes in a GUI model.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The observer design pattern is a behavioural pattern listed among the 23 well-known "Gang of Four" design patterns that address recurring design challenges in order to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, yielding objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The naive approach would be for one object (subject) to directly call specific methods on each dependent object.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This creates tight coupling because the subject must know the concrete types and specific interfaces of all dependent objects, making the code inflexible and hard to extend.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] However, this direct approach may be preferable in performance-critical scenarios (such as low-level kernel structures or real-time systems) where the overhead of abstraction is unacceptable and compile-time optimization is crucial.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] When a subject changes state, all registered observers are notified and updated automatically.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The subject manages its own state while also maintaining a list of observers and notifying them of state changes by calling their `update()` operation.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The responsibility of observers is to register and unregister themselves with a subject (in order to be notified of state changes) and to update their state (to synchronize it with the subject's state) when they are notified.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This approach makes subject and observers loosely coupled through interface standardization.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The subject only needs to know that observers implement the `update()` method—it has no knowledge of observers' concrete types or internal implementation details.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Observers can be added and removed independently at run time.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The observer pattern and the publish–subscribe pattern are closely related and often confused, as both support one-to-many communication between components.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] However, they differ significantly in architecture, degree of coupling, and common use cases.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] In practice, publish–subscribe systems evolved to address several limitations of the observer pattern.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] A typical observer implementation creates a tight coupling between the subject and its observers.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This may limit scalability, flexibility, and maintainability, especially in distributed environments.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Subjects and observers must conform to a shared interface, and both parties are aware of each other’s presence.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] To reduce this coupling, publish–subscribe systems introduce a message broker or event bus that intermediates between publishers and subscribers.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This additional layer removes the need for direct references, allowing systems to evolve independently.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Brokers may also support features like message persistence, delivery guarantees, topic-based filtering, and asynchronous communication.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] In some systems, the observer pattern is used internally to implement subscription mechanisms behind a publish–subscribe interface.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] In other cases, the patterns are applied independently.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] For example, JavaScript libraries and frameworks often offer both observer-like subscriptions (e.g., via callback registration) and decoupled pub-sub mechanisms (e.g., via event emitters or signals).
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Historically, in early graphical operating systems like OS/2 and Microsoft Windows, the terms "publish–subscribe" and "event-driven programming" were often used as synonyms for the observer pattern.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The observer pattern, as formalized in *Design Patterns*, deliberately omits concerns such as unsubscription, notification filtering, delivery guarantees, and message logging.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] These advanced capabilities are typically implemented in robust message queuing systems, where the observer pattern may serve as a foundational mechanism but is not sufficient by itself.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Related patterns include mediator and singleton.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] A common drawback of the observer pattern is the potential for memory leaks, known as the lapsed listener problem.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This occurs when a subject maintains strong references to its observers, preventing them from being garbage collected even if they are no longer needed elsewhere.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Because the pattern typically requires both explicit registration and deregistration (as in the dispose pattern), forgetting to unregister observers can leave dangling references.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This issue can be mitigated by using weak references for observer references, allowing the garbage collector to reclaim observer objects that are no longer in use.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] In some applications, particularly user interfaces, the subject's state may change so frequently that notifying observers on every change is inefficient or counterproductive.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] For example, a view that re-renders on every minor change in a data model might become unresponsive or flicker.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] In such cases, the observer pattern can be modified to decouple notifications *temporally* by introducing a throttling mechanism, such as a timer.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Rather than updating on every state change, the observer polls the subject or is notified at regular intervals, rendering an approximate but stable view of the model.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This approach is commonly used for elements like progress bars, where the underlying process changes state rapidly.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Instead of responding to every minor increment, the observer updates the visual display periodically, improving performance and usability.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This form of temporal decoupling allows observers to remain responsive without being overwhelmed by high-frequency updates, while still reflecting the overall trend or progress of the subject’s state.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] In this UML class diagram, the `Subject` class does not update the state of dependent objects directly.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Instead, `Subject` refers to the `Observer` interface (`update()`) for updating state, which makes the `Subject` independent of how the state of dependent objects is updated.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The `Observer1` and `Observer2` classes implement the `Observer` interface by synchronizing their state with subject's state.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the runtime interactions: The `Observer1` and `Observer2` objects call `attach(this)` on `Subject1` to register themselves.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Assuming that the state of `Subject1` changes, `Subject1` calls `notify()` on itself.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] `notify()` calls `update()` on the registered `Observer1` and `Observer2`objects, which request the changed data (`getState()`) from `Subject1` to update (synchronize) their state.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] While the library classes `java.util.Observer` and `java.util.Observable` exist, they have been deprecated in Java 9 because the model implemented was quite limited.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] Below is an example written in Java that takes keyboard input and handles each input line as an event.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] When a string is supplied from `System.in`, the method `notifyObservers()` is then called in order to notify all observers of the event's occurrence, in the form of an invocation of their update methods.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] C# provides the `IObservable`. and `IObserver` interfaces as well as documentation on how to implement the design pattern.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] JavaScript has a deprecated `Object.observe` function that was a more accurate implementation of the observer pattern.
[src:mobx/observer-pattern] This would fire events upon change to the observed object.
[src:mobx/reactions] Reactions are an important concept to understand, as it is where everything in MobX comes together.
[src:mobx/reactions] The goal of reactions is to model side effects that happen automatically.
[src:mobx/reactions] Their significance is in creating consumers for your observable state and *automatically* running side effects whenever something *relevant* changes.
[src:mobx/reactions] However, with that in mind, it is important to realize that the APIs discussed here should rarely be used.
[src:mobx/reactions] They are often abstracted away in other libraries (like mobx-react) or abstractions specific to your application.
[src:mobx/reactions] But, to grok MobX, let's take a look at how reactions can be created.
[src:mobx/reactions] The simplest way is to use the `autorun` utility.
[src:mobx/reactions] Beyond that, there are also `reaction` and `when`.
[src:mobx/reactions] The `autorun` function accepts one function that should run every time anything it observes changes.
[src:mobx/reactions] It also runs once when you create the `autorun` itself.
[src:mobx/reactions] It only responds to changes in observable state, things you have annotated `observable` or `computed`.
[src:mobx/reactions] Autorun works by running the `effect` in a *reactive context*.
[src:mobx/reactions] During the execution of the provided function, MobX keeps track of all observable and computed values that are directly or indirectly *read* by the effect.
[src:mobx/reactions] Once the function finishes, MobX will collect and subscribe to all observables that were read and wait until any of them changes again.
[src:mobx/reactions] Once they do, the `autorun` will trigger again, repeating the entire process.
[src:mobx/reactions] This is how the example below works like.
[src:mobx/reactions] As you can see in the first two lines of the output above, both `autorun` functions run once when they are initialized.
[src:mobx/reactions] This is all you would see without the `for` loop.
[src:mobx/reactions] For the *"Now I'm hungry"* function, this is every time the `isHungry` computed changes, only one time.
[src:mobx/reactions] `reaction` is like `autorun`, but gives more fine grained control on which observables will be tracked.
[src:mobx/reactions] It takes two functions: the first, *data* function, is tracked and returns the data that is used as input for the second, *effect* function.
[src:mobx/reactions] It is important to note that the side effect *only* reacts to data that was *accessed* in the data function, which might be less than the data that is actually used in the effect function.
[src:mobx/reactions] The typical pattern is that you produce the things you need in your side effect in the *data* function, and in that way control more precisely when the effect triggers.
[src:mobx/reactions] By default, the result of the *data* function has to change in order for the *effect* function to be triggered.
[src:mobx/reactions] Unlike `autorun`, the side effect won't run once when initialized, but only after the data expression returns a new value for the first time.
[src:mobx/reactions] In the example below, the reaction is only triggered once, when `isHungry` changes.
[src:mobx/reactions] Changes to `giraffe.energyLevel`, which is used by the *effect* function, do not cause the *effect* function to be executed.
[src:mobx/reactions] If you wanted `reaction` to respond to this as well, you would have to also access it in the *data* function and return it.
[src:mobx/reactions] `when` observes and runs the given *predicate* function until it returns `true`.
[src:mobx/reactions] Once that happens, the given *effect* function is executed and the autorunner is disposed.
[src:mobx/reactions] The `when` function returns a disposer, allowing you to cancel it manually, unless you don't pass in a second `effect` function, in which case it returns a `Promise`.
[src:mobx/reactions] `when` is really useful for disposing or canceling of things in a reactive way.
[src:mobx/reactions] As soon as `isVisible` becomes `false`, the `dispose` method is called that then does some cleanup for `MyResource`.
[src:mobx/reactions] If no `effect` function is provided, `when` returns a `Promise`.
[src:mobx/reactions] This combines nicely with `async / await` to let you wait for changes in observable state.
[src:mobx/reactions] To cancel `when` prematurely, it is possible to call `.cancel()` on the promise returned by itself.
[src:mobx/reactions] Autorun tracks only the observables that are read during the synchronous execution of the provided function, but it won't track anything that happens asynchronously.
[src:mobx/reactions] Autorun won't track observables that are read by an action invoked by the autorun, as actions are always *untracked*.
[src:mobx/reactions] For more examples on what precisely MobX will and will not react to, check out the Understanding reactivity section.
[src:mobx/reactions] For a more detailed technical breakdown on how tracking works, read the blog post Becoming fully reactive: an in-depth explanation of MobX.
[src:mobx/reactions] The functions passed to `autorun`, `reaction` and `when` are only garbage collected if all objects they observe are garbage collected themselves.
[src:mobx/reactions] In principle, they keep waiting forever for new changes to happen in the observables they use.
[src:mobx/reactions] To be able to stop them from waiting until forever has passed, they all return a disposer function that can be used to stop them and unsubscribe from any observables they used.
[src:mobx/reactions] We strongly recommend to always use the disposer function that is returned from these methods as soon as their side effect is no longer needed.
[src:mobx/reactions] Failing to do so can lead to memory leaks.
[src:mobx/reactions] The `reaction` argument that is passed as second argument to the effect functions of `reaction` and `autorun`, can be used to prematurely clean up the reaction as well by calling `reaction.dispose()`.
[src:mobx/reactions] In environments that support Explicit Resource Management, the disposer function includes a `[Symbol.dispose]` method that can be used to dispose of the reaction.
[src:mobx/reactions] This can be useful when disposing of several reactions simultaneously or when disposing of reactions alongside other Disposables.
[src:mobx/reactions] As it was already said, you won't create reactions very often.
[src:mobx/reactions] It might very well be that your application doesn't use any of these APIs directly, and the only way reactions are constructed is indirectly, through for example `observer` from the mobx-react bindings.
[src:mobx/reactions] **Reactions shouldn't update other observables**: Is the reaction going to modify other observables?
[src:mobx/reactions] If the answer is yes, typically the observable you want to update should be annotated as a `computed` value instead.
[src:mobx/reactions] For example, if a collection of todos is altered, don't use a reaction to compute the amount of `remainingTodos`, but annotate `remainingTodos` as a computed value.
[src:mobx/reactions] That will lead to much clearer and easier to debug code.
[src:mobx/reactions] Reactions should not compute new data, but only cause effects.
[src:mobx/reactions] **Reactions should be independent**: Does your code rely on some other reaction having to run first?
[src:mobx/reactions] If that is the case, you probably either violated the first rule, or the new reaction you are about to create should be merged into the one it is depending upon.
[src:mobx/reactions] MobX does not guarantee the order in which reactions will be run.
[src:mobx/reactions] There are real-life scenarios that do not fit in the above principles.
[src:mobx/reactions] That is why they are *principles*, not *laws*.
[src:mobx/reactions] But, the exceptions are rare so only violate them as a last resort.
[src:mobx/reactions] The behavior of `autorun`, `reaction` and `when` can be further fine-tuned by passing in an `options` argument as shown in the usages above.
[src:mobx/reactions] This string is used as a debug name for this reaction in the Spy event listeners and MobX developer tools.
[src:mobx/reactions] Boolean indicating that the *effect* function should immediately be triggered after the first run of the *data* function.
[src:mobx/reactions] Number of milliseconds that can be used to throttle the effect function.
[src:mobx/reactions] If zero (default), no throttling happens.
[src:mobx/reactions] Set a limited amount of time that `when` will wait for.
[src:mobx/reactions] If the deadline passes, `when` will reject / throw.
[src:mobx/reactions] An AbortSignal object instance; can be used as an alternative method for disposal.
[src:mobx/reactions] When used with promise version of `when`, the promise rejects with the "WHEN_ABORTED" error.
[src:mobx/reactions] By default, any exception thrown inside an reaction will be logged, but not further thrown.
[src:mobx/reactions] This is to make sure that an exception in one reaction does not prevent the scheduled execution of other, possibly unrelated reactions.
[src:mobx/reactions] This also allows reactions to recover from exceptions.
[src:mobx/reactions] Throwing an exception does not break the tracking done by MobX, so subsequent runs of the reaction might complete normally again if the cause for the exception is removed.
[src:mobx/reactions] This option allows overriding that behavior.
[src:mobx/reactions] It is possible to set a global error handler or to disable catching errors completely using configure.
[src:mobx/reactions] Set a custom scheduler to determine how re-running the autorun function should be scheduled.
[src:mobx/reactions] If specified, this comparer function is used to compare the previous and next values produced by the *data* function.
[src:mobx/reactions] The *effect* function is only invoked if this function returns false.
[src:mobx/reactions] Check out the Built-in comparers section.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:mobx/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:mobx/state-management] This is especially the case when the state of any particular message or form on the page depends on factors outside of the current page, or available throughout several pages.
[src:mobx/state-management] For example, consider a user who is logged in and sees the 'welcome' message on their first visit to any page, but not on subsequent page visits.
[src:mobx/state-management] Does each page manage the state of the user being logged in?
[src:mobx/state-management] That would create too much copy pasting and duplication of code.
[src:mobx/state-management] Instead, you can use a state management pattern for handling messages (this may also include handling error messages and informative messages, along with the described welcome message) and then call this to receive a message as it becomes available.
[src:mobx/state-management] Examples of state management libraries include Pinia as a state management library for the Vue.js JavaScript framework.
[src:mobx/state-management] For the Angular framework there exist multiple community options: NgRx (based on Redux, with a lightweight alternative using Signals), NGXS and RxAngular.
[src:mobx/state-management] Redux is a general-purpose state management library that can be used with any of the above frameworks or other view libraries, but is very commonly used with the React library.
[src:mobx/state-management] As the documentation in Redux alludes, many of these state management libraries are lightweight and can be replaced by each other.
[src:mobx/state-management] It's also possible to roll your own based on a publish–subscribe pattern where your interface components (like form fields, buttons, and messages) listen to a centralized data store in your application for new changes.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Let's take a closer look at these concepts below, or alternatively, in the 10 minute introduction to MobX and React, where you can interactively dive deeper into these concepts step by step and build a simple Todo list app.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Some might recognise the concept of "Signals" in the concepts described below.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] This is correct, MobX is a signal based state management library avant la lettre.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Store state in any data structure you like: plain objects, arrays, classes, cyclic data structures or references.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] It doesn't matter for the workings of MobX.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Just make sure that all properties you want to change over time are marked as `observable` so MobX can track them.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Using `observable` is like turning a property of an object into a spreadsheet cell.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] But unlike spreadsheets, these values can not only be primitive values, but also references, objects and arrays.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Tip: Prefer classes, plain objects or decorators?
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] This example can be shortened using `makeAutoObservable`, but by being explicit we can showcase the different concepts in greater detail.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Note that MobX doesn't dictate an object style, plain objects instead can be used as well, as can decorators for even more concise classes.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] But what about `toggle`, which we marked as `action`?
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] An *action* is any piece of code that changes the *state*.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] User events, backend data pushes, scheduled events, etc.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] An action is like a user that enters a new value into a spreadsheet cell.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] In the `Todo` model above you can see that we have a `toggle` method that changes the value of `finished`.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] It is recommended that you mark any piece of code that changes `observable`'s as an `action`.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] That way MobX can automatically apply transactions for effortless optimal performance.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Using actions helps you structure your code and prevents you from inadvertently changing state when you don't intend to.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Methods that modify state are called *actions* in MobX terminology.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] In contrast to *views*, which compute new information based on the current state.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Every method should serve at most one of those two goals.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] When starting with MobX, people tend to overuse reactions.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] The golden rule is, always use `computed` if you want to create a value based on the current state.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] To create a *computed* value, define a property using a JS getter function `get` and mark it as `computed` with `makeObservable`.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] MobX will ensure that `unfinishedTodoCount` is updated automatically when a todo is added or when one of the `finished` properties is modified.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] These computations resemble formulas in spreadsheet programs like MS Excel.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] They update automatically, but only when required.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] That is, if something is interested in their outcome.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] For you as a user to be able to see a change in state or computed values on the screen, a *reaction* that repaints a part of the GUI is needed.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Reactions are similar to computed values, but instead of producing information, they produce side effects like printing to the console, making network requests, incrementally updating React component tree to patch the DOM, etc.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] In short, reactions bridge the worlds of reactive and imperative programming.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] By far the most used form of reactions are UI components.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Note that it is possible to trigger side effects from both actions and reactions.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Side effects that have a clear, explicit origin from which they can be triggered, such as making a network request when submitting a form, should be triggered explicitly from the relevant event handler.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] If you are using React, you can make your components reactive by wrapping them with the `observer` function from the bindings package you've chosen during installation.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] In this example, we're going to use the more lightweight `mobx-react-lite` package.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] `observer` converts React components into derivations of the data they render.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] When using MobX there are no smart or dumb components.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] All components render smartly, but are defined in a dumb manner.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] MobX will simply make sure the components are always re-rendered whenever needed, and never more than that.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] So the `onClick` handler in the above example will force the proper `TodoView` component to re-render as it uses the `toggle` action, but will only cause the `TodoListView` component to re-render if the number of unfinished tasks has changed.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] And if you would remove the `Tasks left` line (or put it into a separate component), the `TodoListView` component would no longer re-render when ticking a task.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] To learn more about how React works with MobX, check out the React integration section.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] You will need them rarely, but they can be created using the `autorun`, `reaction` or `when` functions to fit your specific situations.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Why does a new message get printed every time the `unfinishedTodoCount` is changed?
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] To learn more about how MobX determines which observables need to be reacted to, check out the Understanding reactivity section.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] MobX uses a uni-directional data flow where *actions* change the *state*, which in turn updates all affected *views*.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] All *derivations* are updated **synchronously** by default.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] This means that, for example, *actions* can safely inspect a computed value directly after altering the *state*.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] *Computed values* are updated **lazily**.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] Any computed value that is not actively in use will not be updated until it is needed for a side effect (I/O).
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] If a view is no longer in use it will be garbage collected automatically.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] All *computed values* should be **pure**.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] They are not supposed to change *state*.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] To learn more about the background context, check out the fundamental principles behind MobX.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] You can play with the above examples yourself on CodeSandbox.
[src:mobx/the-gist-of-mobx] If you find it hard to adopt the mental model of MobX, configure it to be very strict and warn you at runtime whenever you deviate from these patterns.
